Date: Mon 7 Aug 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Presna Latina, 6 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com/Article.asp?ID=%7BD65AB4B6-6925-4026-B6BD-655F7C6782A3%7D&language=EN>


Avian Flu Alert in 29 Thailand Provinces
----------------------------------------
The Thailand red sanitary alert extended to 29 provinces due to the
appearance of avian flu cases in those territories, reported the
Minister of Agriculture and Cooperatives, Sudarat Keyuraphan.

A 17-year-old boy and a young man of 27 died from the H5N1 virus over
the last 2 weeks, while dozens of patients with similar symptoms were
declared in quarantine and submitted to strict clinical observation.

Provinces declared under "high avian flu risk" are: Bangkok, Sing
Buri, Angthong, Ayutthaya, Nonthaburi, Suphan Buri, Chai Nat, Pathum
Thani, Lop Buri, Chachoengsao, Nakhon Nayok, Nakhon Phanom, Kalasin,
Khon Kaen, Phichit, Kamphaeng Phet, Nakhon Sawan & Chaiyaphum.

Also on the red list are Nakhon Phatom, Phitsanulok, Udon Thani,
Kanchanaburi, Samut Prakan, Nakhon Ratchasima, Prachin Buri,
Phetchabun, Uttaradit, Sukhothai & Uthai Thani. [It would be
helpful to note what "red sanitary alert" stands for; see
commentary]. A 27-year-old patient died on Thursday [3 Aug 2006] in
this last province.

Thailand was one of the countries worst hit by avian flu in 2004,
when the virus seriously affected several Asian countries, including
China and Viet Nam.

Up to now, official sources have confirmed 24 [human] cases, of which 16 were
fatal. The Thai food industry has reported losses in the 2nd quarter of the
present year [2006] due to a fall in prices and a drop in poultry sales due to
the scare generated by the fever.

--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
<jdudley@eaicorp.com>

